				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Michael Bloomberg, Now a U.N. Climate Envoy, Presses the Case for Urban Action</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Andrew C. Revkin			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-19T17:08:48+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 19, 2014 1:08 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 19, 2014 1:08 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/09/19/michael-bloomberg-now-a-u-n-climate-envoy-presses-the-case-for-urban-action/" data-title="Michael Bloomberg, Now a U.N. Climate Envoy, Presses the Case for Urban Action" data-description="Michael Bloomberg, a mayor turned U.N. climate envoy, explains what cities can do to blunt climate change and its impacts.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/11/21/nyregion/20cityroom-poll/20cityroom-poll-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/11/21/nyregion/20cityroom-poll/20cityroom-poll-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/11/21/nyregion/20cityroom-poll/20cityroom-poll-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000001913994" width="480" height="319" alt="Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg viewing damage from Hurricane Sandy in Breezy Point, Queens, in late October, 2012."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="319"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg viewing damage from Hurricane Sandy in Breezy Point, Queens, in late October, 2012.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stan Honda/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I recently had a chance to ask <a title="Michael Bloomberg in The New York Times" href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/michael_r_bloomberg/index.html">former New York City Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg</a> about the fresh push he&#8217;s making for urban action to blunt climate impacts and greenhouse gas emissions as the new <a href="//www.un.org/climatechange/summit/2014/01/secretary-general-appoints-michael-bloomberg-of-united-states-special-envoy-for-cities-and-climate-change/">United Nations Special Envoy for Cities and Climate Change</a>. He&#8217;ll be a very busy man next week, as the city hosts the <a title="People's Climate March" href="//peoplesclimate.org/march/">People&#8217;s Climate March</a>, a <a href="//www.un.org/climatechange/summit/">U.N. &#8220;summit&#8221; on climate change</a> and <a href="//www.climateweeknyc.org">Climate Week</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//www.onearth.org/articles/2014/09/exclusive-mikebloomberg-talks-cites-and-climate-change-with-revkin">full interview is in OnEarth</a>, a magazine published by the Natural Resources Defense Council. Here are several of the question and answers, followed by a link to the rest:</p>
<blockquote>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the energy and resilience fronts, it&#8217;s pretty clear that the challenges facing mature, developed-nation cities like New York or London are different from the ones being faced by fast-growing metropolises in developing nationsâcities likeÂ <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2009/09/24/world/asia/24delta.html?pagewanted=all&amp;_r=1&amp;">Ho Chi Minh City</a>Â orÂ <a href="//www.worldbank.org/en/news/feature/2013/08/19/coastal-cities-at-highest-risk-floods">Guangzhou</a>. As your administration found, for instance,Â <a href="//www.nyc.gov/html/gbee/downloads/pdf/mayors_carbon_challenge_progress_report.pdf">80 percent of the buildings</a>Â in New York City today will still be in use in 2050, meaning that a push for energy thrift is largely one of retrofitting. In Asia and Africa, by comparison, much of the urban infrastructure has yet to be built, and there may be less capital and capacity for making energy-smart investments.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What are the most glaring opportunities for sharp cuts in fossil-generated energy in these two situations? <span id="more-53160"></span></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In fast-growing cities that are still taking shape, smart city planning can make a big difference. Cities can build sustainability into their fabric as they grow. They can incorporate energy-efficient building practices from the beginning. They can embrace density and mass transit, instead of sprawl and highways. Itâs true that some of these policies require significant up-front investments, but they pay off in the long run by lowering energy costs, improving public health and making a city more attractive to peopleâwho, in turn, help attract investment. Creating a city that people want to live in is the best way to create a city that businesses want to invest in.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For the most part, older big cities have two main areas they can focus on to significantly reduce emissions: buildings and transportation. On the buildings side, retrofits can make a big difference. So can checking and adjusting a buildingâs systems to make sure they are working as efficiently and effectively as they should be. This was one of the single most effective things we did to reduce New York Cityâs carbon footprint. On the transportation side, expanding mass transit to reduce congestion is critically important, and by âmass transit,â I mean anything from subways and commuter rails to buses and bikes.Â  Electric vehicles also represent a big opportunityâboth private and city-owned vehicles. Cities can help build out the infrastructure to speed the transition, which is also something we did in New York.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As for resilience in the face of rising seas and storm surges, you gave a creditable speech on climate change adaptation in your final year in office, but it had a classicÂ â<a href="//www.nyc.gov/portal/site/nycgov/menuitem.c0935b9a57bb4ef3daf2f1c701c789a0/index.jsp?pageID=mayor_press_release&amp;catID=1194&amp;doc_name=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nyc.gov%2Fhtml%2Fom%2Fhtml%2F2013a%2Fpr200-13.html&amp;cc=unused1978&amp;rc=1194&amp;ndi=1">no retreat</a>âÂ theme, centering on this line:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â[A]s New Yorkers, we cannot and will not abandon our waterfront. Itâs one of our greatest assets. We must protect it, not retreat from it.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nearly all of the scientists and engineers I&#8217;ve interviewed in 25 years of writing on global warming see the hardening of shorelines as an inevitable failure, given the forecast of centuries of rising seas. At the same time, I recognize that there&#8217;s no wayâyetâthat a mayor could stay in office with a campaign saying, âWeÂ willÂ ____ retreat,â regardless of what adverb filled that gap (for example, âsmartlyâ).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do you think it&#8217;s possible to create a political environment that truly reflects our coastal realities in the coming decades?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Remember: four of every five New York City residents live on an island. Manhattan is entirely surrounded by water. So is Staten Island. Brooklyn and Queens are on an island. And the Bronx is surrounded by water on three sides. So I was stating what should be obvious: weâre a waterfront city, and we must learn to live with rising sea levels.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And weÂ can. If you look at what happened during Sandy, buildings that were built according to modern, higher construction standards fared far better than those that werenât. Something like 95% of the buildings that were destroyed or severely damaged during Sandy were built more than 50 years ago, before modern building code standards. New infrastructureâincluding parks that we built along the waterfront that took climate risks into accountâsuffered relatively little damage, or even no damage.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The future of waterfront cities, whether itâs New York or Miami, or anywhere elseâ and most of the worldâs major cities are coastal citiesâdepends on our ability to adapt to rising sea levels and climate change. You canât pick up Manhattan and move it inland, but youÂ canÂ adopt policies that better protect it from storms.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of the least appreciated aspects of urban life that offers real promise in cutting climate change risks is the ability to create a new generation of energy and climate problem solvers within city schools, at all levels. In the Bronx earlier this year, I was thrilled to tag along with students on a âfield tripâ to the boiler room at the publicÂ <a href="//www.solar1.org/nyt-praises-solar-one-schools-creative-education-methods/">High School for Energy and Technology</a>, where the custodian and teachers revealed the energy choices that make a schoolâor any other buildingârun.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!--more--></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!--more--></p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/19/blogs/dotboiler/dotboiler-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/19/blogs/dotboiler/dotboiler-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/19/blogs/dotboiler/dotboiler-blog480.jpg" id="100000003125774" width="480" height="284" alt="In the boiler room at theÂ &lt;a href=&quot;//www.solar1.org/nyt-praises-solar-one-schools-creative-education-methods/&quot;&gt;High School for Energy and Technology in the Bronx&lt;/a&gt;, students are briefed on energy systems and climate change by the custodian and a teacher."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="284"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">In the boiler room at theÂ <a href="//www.solar1.org/nyt-praises-solar-one-schools-creative-education-methods/">High School for Energy and Technology in the Bronx</a>, students are briefed on energy systems and climate change by the custodian and a teacher.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What innovations in education have you witnessed that you feel will give cities, and society more generally, the capacity to thrive in this changing environment?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A great example with a similar focus to the one youâve just described isÂ <a href="//www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20131014/long-island-city/energy-tech-hs-principal-preps-students-for-college-career">Energy Tech</a>, one of the six-year high schools we created to connect students directly to 21stÂ century industries. We teamed up with Con Ed, National Grid, and CUNY [City University of New York] to create it. The kids who go there get to take college-level classes and get hands-on internship experience at two of the biggest energy utility companies in the nation, where theyâll be exposed to many of the major challenges surrounding energy and climate. After six years, they graduate with an Associateâs Degree, as well as a high-school diploma. Then they can decide whether they want to continue with college or enter the workforce.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A high-school diploma is no longer the ticket into the middle class that it was when I was growing up. We have to give students the skills that the global economy demands, and the cities that do the best job of that will be well-positioned to grow and thrive.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I wrote a while back that the United Nationsâ laudable mission of developing goals, which have mostly been aimed at ending deep poverty and its attendant ills, might now need to be expanded such that new goals were being developed for, and pursued by, the worldâs most prosperous communities as well. (The piece was titled â<a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/21/do-the-top-billion-need-new-goals/">Do the Top Billion Need New Goals?</a>â) Clearly, weâll never live in a world where everybody on the planet occupies some happy median, but nevertheless, do you similarly believe that we need to embrace a new definition of âsuccessâ in this coming century of planetary constraints?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The greatest engine for reducing poverty and disease has been capitalism, and the rise in living standards that has accompanied it. We shouldnât turn our back on that. And at the same time, as our technology advances, our method of producing and consuming things is becoming more efficient, and it will continue to. So we donât have to choose between raising living standards and saving the planet. In New York City, we were able to create a record number of jobs while alsoÂ <a href="//sustainablecitiescollective.com/david-thorpe/211366/departing-bloomberg-says-new-york-citys-air-cleaner-and-greenhouse-gas-emissions">driving down our carbon footprint</a>Â by 19%. Between 2005 and 2013, the cityâs population grew by about a quarter-million peopleâbut our overall energy consumption stayed essentially the same. Progress like this is happening in cities all around the world, and as cities learn which policies and technologies are most effective, their progress is accelerating. The worldâs cities are growing fast. And thatâs a good thing for our planet.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.onearth.org/articles/2014/09/exclusive-mikebloomberg-talks-cites-and-climate-change-with-revkin">Please read the rest here.</a></p>
